// ============================================================================
//   new_intelligence_L1.rs — DQN heterotroph brain pool   (PSEUDOCODE ONLY)
//                                                                    rev 2
// ============================================================================
//
// This file is a DESIGN DOCUMENT, not compilable Rust. It sketches a drop-in
// replacement for `intelligence_level_1_hetero.rs` based on Q-learning with
// experience replay and a target network — exactly the recipe from Mnih et al.
// 2015 ("Human-level control through deep reinforcement learning", Nature).
//
// Why DQN and not REINFORCE / PPO / SAC:
//   • DQN is the simplest deep-RL algorithm that reliably learns from sparse,
//     delayed rewards in a discrete action space — which is exactly what prey
//     pursuit is once we discretise heading.
//   • It sidesteps every Tier-1 algorithm bug we found in the REINFORCE
//     implementation (see intelligence_analysis.txt §EXECUTIVE SUMMARY).
//   • Per-organism networks fit the existing batched-pool architecture
//     unchanged — the pool is still N independent rows of a [N, ...] tensor.
//
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//   CHANGES FROM REV 1  (see "DESIGN NOTES — REV 2" at the bottom for full
//   rationale; the executive summary is here)
// ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
//   FIX A — Terminal transitions are now recorded. In rev 1, an organism that
//           died between brain ticks never pushed the (s, a, r, terminal)
//           transition that taught the network "this state-action killed me".
//           Death penalty propagation was therefore impossible. Now handled
//           by free_brains_l1_hetero (§7) before the slot is released.
//
//   FIX B — ε is per-slot, not global. The rev 1 global counter caused late-
//           generation organisms to inherit a near-zero ε despite having an
//           empty replay buffer and (often) inherited weights from a
//           genealogically unrelated previous tenant. ε now resets on slot
//           assignment and decays per-slot. The global decisions_made counter
//           is retained for telemetry only.
//
//   FIX C — Prey encoding is permutation-invariant. Rev 1's "top-4 nearest,
//           sorted by distance" produced a different state vector whenever
//           two nearby prey swapped distance rank, even though the world was
//           effectively identical. Replaced with 8 angular bins in the
//           organism's body frame, each reporting (nearest distance, occupied)
//           — same STATE_DIM = 18, no rank instability.
//
// Out of scope (deliberately):
//   • Prioritised experience replay      — uniform sampling is simpler.
//   • Double DQN / dueling DQN           — incremental; not needed first.
//   • Distributional / noisy nets / NAF  — experimental.
//   • Recurrent state / LSTM             — body-frame state + replay is
//                                          enough for the Markov assumption.
//   • Continuous-action methods (SAC,    — discrete actions are sufficient
//     DDPG)                                for pursuit.
//
// All constants and shapes are placeholders; numbers chosen as "known-good
// DQN defaults" and to be tuned empirically.
//
// ============================================================================
//   1. CONSTANTS
// ============================================================================

const STATE_DIM:    usize = 18           // see §3 for new layout (rev 2)
const HIDDEN:       usize = 64
const N_ACTIONS:    usize = 9            // 8 compass dirs + 1 "stop"

const GAMMA:        f32 = 0.95           // discount; short horizon for pursuit.
                                         // With BRAIN_TICK_INTERVAL = 100ms,
                                         // effective horizon ≈ 20 ticks ≈ 2s.
                                         // If the tick interval changes, revisit.
const LR:           f32 = 5e-4           // Adam learning rate
const HUBER_DELTA:  f32 = 1.0            // Huber loss transition

const REPLAY_CAPACITY: usize = 1024      // per-organism ring buffer size
const BATCH_PER_SLOT:  usize = 32        // transitions sampled per training step per organism
const MIN_REPLAY:      usize = 64        // do not train a slot until buffer has this many

const EPSILON_START:       f32 = 1.00    // start fully random
const EPSILON_END:         f32 = 0.05    // permanent floor for exploration
const EPSILON_DECAY_STEPS: u32 = 4_000   // PER-SLOT decisions over which ε ramps.
                                         // Rev 1 used 100k globally, which at
                                         // ~80 hetero × 10 Hz burned out in
                                         // ~2 min and starved late generations.
                                         // 4k per slot ≈ 7 min of personal
                                         // experience before ε hits floor.

const TARGET_SYNC_STEPS: u32 = 1_000     // hard-copy online → target every K training steps
const GRAD_CLIP_NORM:    f32 = 10.0      // ||grad||₂ clamp

const MAX_SPEED:    f32 = 20.0           // matches existing apply_movement

// Death penalty (FIX A). Applied as the reward of the terminal transition,
// in the same clamped-[-1, 1] units as the running reward. Chosen large
// enough to dominate any single Δenergy step.
const DEATH_REWARD: f32 = -1.0

// Prey encoding parameters (FIX C — see §3).
const N_PREY_BINS:  usize = 8            // angular sectors around body frame
const PREY_FIELDS:  usize = 2            // (nearest_distance, occupied) per bin


// ============================================================================
//   2. DISCRETE ACTION SPACE
// ============================================================================
//
// Nine actions. Eight are unit XZ-plane direction vectors at MAX_SPEED.
// The ninth ("stop") halts movement without changing the current heading.
// Eight directions is fine-grained enough for pursuit in a 2D world — finer
// quantisation only matters near the prey, where speed control matters more.
//
// NOTE on STOP and yaw: apply_movement must not zero or drift the organism's
// rotation when movement_speed == 0. Body-frame state encoding (§3) reads
// transform.rotation; if STOP silently rotates the body, the body frame
// becomes non-Markov w.r.t. the policy. Verify in apply_movement that
// rotation is only updated when speed > 0 AND movement_direction is non-zero.
//
//   index   direction (x, z)            label
//   ─────   ─────────────────           ─────
//     0     ( 0.000,  1.000)            N
//     1     ( 0.707,  0.707)            NE
//     2     ( 1.000,  0.000)            E
//     3     ( 0.707, -0.707)            SE
//     4     ( 0.000, -1.000)            S
//     5     (-0.707, -0.707)            SW
//     6     (-1.000,  0.000)            W
//     7     (-0.707,  0.707)            NW
//     8     ( 0.000,  0.000)            STOP (speed = 0, dir unchanged)

const ACTION_DIRS: [(f32, f32); N_ACTIONS] = [
    ( 0.000,  1.000),  ( 0.707,  0.707),  ( 1.000,  0.000),  ( 0.707, -0.707),
    ( 0.000, -1.000),  (-0.707, -0.707),  (-1.000,  0.000),  (-0.707,  0.707),
    ( 0.000,  0.000),
]


// ============================================================================
//   3. STATE VECTOR  (BODY FRAME, ANGULAR BINS)        [REWRITTEN IN REV 2]
// ============================================================================
//
// State is encoded in the organism's OWN frame, so heading does not appear
// explicitly — the same prey configuration produces the same state regardless
// of which way the organism is facing. This eliminates §S1 of
// intelligence_analysis.txt by construction.
//
// Rev 1 used "top-4 nearest prey, sorted by distance". Two problems:
//   (i)   When two prey were near-equidistant, tick-to-tick rank flips
//         produced different state vectors for effectively identical worlds.
//         The network had to learn that two state vectors with permuted slots
//         meant the same thing, from sparse data.
//   (ii)  Prey #4 vs no prey #4 was a discontinuity at the radius edge.
//
// FIX C: replace with N_PREY_BINS angular sectors (8) around the body frame.
// Each sector reports the distance to the NEAREST prey inside that sector
// (or 1.0 = max if empty) and a binary "occupied" flag. The sectorisation is
// done in body frame, so it inherits the rotation invariance of the rev 1
// design. Permuting prey within a sector doesn't change the encoding;
// permuting across sectors changes it the same way the world changed.
//
//   index   field                                  source
//   ─────   ──────────────────────────────────     ─────────────────────────
//   [0]     own_energy / max_energy                Organism
//   [1]     own_speed / MAX_SPEED                  Organism.movement_speed
//   [2..18] 8 angular bins × 2 fields:             WorldModelGrid +
//             [2 + 2k + 0] nearest_dist_in_bin_k   Transform.yaw rotation
//             [2 + 2k + 1] is_occupied (0 or 1)
//
// Bin k covers body-frame angles [k·45°, (k+1)·45°), with bin 0 starting at
// body-frame "forward" (+z axis after inverse-yaw rotation). Distance is
// normalised by WORLD_MODEL_RADIUS and clamped to [0, 1]; an empty bin
// stores distance = 1.0 (max), occupied = 0.0.
//
// Why distance = 1.0 (not 0.0) for empty bins: a future prey appearing at
// the radius edge produces distance ≈ 1.0 with occupied = 1.0 — continuous
// in the distance channel, discontinuous only in the flag. This is much
// easier for a ReLU MLP than rev 1's "all zeros means missing" convention,
// which made "missing" look like "very close" in the distance channel.

fn encode_state(
    organism: &Organism,
    transform: &Transform,
    grid: &WorldModelGrid,
) -> [f32; STATE_DIM]:

    let mut s = [0.0; STATE_DIM]

    // Channel 0: own energy.
    s[0] = (organism.energy / organism.max_energy).clamp(0.0, 1.0)

    // Channel 1: own speed.
    s[1] = (organism.movement_speed / MAX_SPEED).clamp(0.0, 1.0)

    // Initialise all bins as empty (distance = 1.0, occupied = 0.0).
    for k in 0..N_PREY_BINS:
        s[2 + 2*k + 0] = 1.0
        s[2 + 2*k + 1] = 0.0

    // Inverse-yaw rotation: world coords → body coords.
    //   body_x =  cos(yaw) · world_x + sin(yaw) · world_z
    //   body_z = -sin(yaw) · world_x + cos(yaw) · world_z
    //
    let yaw   = transform.rotation.to_euler(YXZ).1
    let cos_y = cos(yaw)
    let sin_y = sin(yaw)

    // Consider ALL prey within WORLD_MODEL_RADIUS, not just top-k. The grid
    // already does the radius cull; the inner loop is at most ~tens of items
    // and runs once per organism per tick. Sectorisation reduces all of them
    // to 8 numbers regardless of count.
    let neighbours = grid.within_radius(transform.translation.xz(), WORLD_MODEL_RADIUS)
    for n in neighbours:
        let rel = n.position.xz() - transform.translation.xz()
        let body_x =  cos_y * rel.x + sin_y * rel.z
        let body_z = -sin_y * rel.x + cos_y * rel.z

        let dist = sqrt(body_x*body_x + body_z*body_z)
        if dist > WORLD_MODEL_RADIUS: continue

        // atan2 returns (-π, π]; shift to [0, 2π) then quantise to N bins.
        // angle is measured CCW from the body-frame +z axis (forward).
        let mut angle = atan2(body_x, body_z)         // x first → angle from +z
        if angle < 0.0: angle += 2.0 * PI
        let bin = ((angle / (2.0 * PI)) * N_PREY_BINS as f32) as usize
        let bin = bin.min(N_PREY_BINS - 1)            // guard against == 8 at wrap

        let norm_dist = (dist / WORLD_MODEL_RADIUS).clamp(0.0, 1.0)
        let cur = s[2 + 2*bin + 0]
        if norm_dist < cur:                            // keep the NEAREST per bin
            s[2 + 2*bin + 0] = norm_dist
            s[2 + 2*bin + 1] = 1.0

    return s


// ============================================================================
//   4. NETWORK
// ============================================================================
//
// Two hidden layers, ReLU, linear output (Q-values are unbounded).
// He-normal init for the hidden layers (standard for ReLU).
// Tiny uniform init for the output layer so initial Q-values are near zero —
// keeps the first few updates from drifting wildly.
//
// Per-row batched matmul exactly as the existing pool:
//   forward shape:  [BATCH, STATE_DIM] → [BATCH, N_ACTIONS]
//   weights shape:  w1 [N, STATE_DIM, HIDDEN], etc.
//
// `BATCH` is BATCH_PER_SLOT during training, 1 during action selection.

struct QNetMlp:
    w1: Param<Tensor[N, STATE_DIM, HIDDEN]>
    b1: Param<Tensor[N, HIDDEN]>
    w2: Param<Tensor[N, HIDDEN, HIDDEN]>
    b2: Param<Tensor[N, HIDDEN]>
    w3: Param<Tensor[N, HIDDEN, N_ACTIONS]>
    b3: Param<Tensor[N, N_ACTIONS]>

    fn new(device, n):
        // He-normal: std = sqrt(2 / fan_in)
        w1 = NormalInit(std = sqrt(2.0 / STATE_DIM)).init([n, STATE_DIM, HIDDEN], device)
        w2 = NormalInit(std = sqrt(2.0 / HIDDEN   )).init([n, HIDDEN, HIDDEN], device)
        // Small uniform init on the output → Q-values start near zero.
        w3 = UniformInit(-1e-3, +1e-3).init([n, HIDDEN, N_ACTIONS], device)
        b1, b2, b3 = ZeroInit.init(...)
        return Self { w1, b1, w2, b2, w3, b3 }

    // x: [n, BATCH, STATE_DIM]  → out: [n, BATCH, N_ACTIONS]
    // (BATCH = 1 for action selection, BATCH = BATCH_PER_SLOT for training.)
    fn forward(x):
        h = relu(batched_matmul(x, w1) + b1.unsqueeze(BATCH dim))
        h = relu(batched_matmul(h, w2) + b2.unsqueeze(BATCH dim))
        q = batched_matmul(h, w3) + b3.unsqueeze(BATCH dim)
        return q

    // Hard copy of every Param's underlying tensor — for target sync.
    // No autograd link between source and copy.
    fn clone_weights_into(other: &mut QNetMlp):
        other.w1 = self.w1.clone_no_grad()
        ... same for b1, w2, b2, w3, b3.

    // Reset ONE slot's weights in-place. Used on slot assignment when we
    // want a newborn to start from a clean prior instead of inheriting
    // weights from the slot's previous tenant. See §7 / FIX B note for
    // the inheritance-vs-reset trade-off; currently we INHERIT and rely on
    // the per-slot ε reset to recover exploration. This method is provided
    // for the experimental "fresh weights per birth" path documented in
    // §12 step 9.
    fn reinit_slot(slot: usize, device):
        // Write a single row of each Param tensor with the same init
        // distributions as new(). Must NOT touch the autograd graph of
        // other slots. In Burn this is a no-grad scatter into the
        // underlying tensor; Param is reattached afterwards.
        scatter_row(self.w1, slot, NormalInit(std = sqrt(2.0 / STATE_DIM)))
        scatter_row(self.w2, slot, NormalInit(std = sqrt(2.0 / HIDDEN   )))
        scatter_row(self.w3, slot, UniformInit(-1e-3, +1e-3))
        scatter_row(self.b1, slot, ZeroInit)
        scatter_row(self.b2, slot, ZeroInit)
        scatter_row(self.b3, slot, ZeroInit)


// ============================================================================
//   5. POOL RESOURCE                                   [MODIFIED IN REV 2]
// ============================================================================

struct BrainPoolL1Hetero:
    n: usize                                  // = OrganismPoolSize
    online: QNetMlp                           // the network we train
    target: QNetMlp                           // periodically synced copy
    optimizer: AdamOptimizer
    device: CudaDevice

    // Slot bookkeeping (identical to existing pool):
    free: Vec<u32>                            // free-list of slot indices
    map:  HashMap<Entity, u32>                // entity → slot

    // Per-slot "last decision" cache, for building (s, a, r, s') tuples:
    prev_state:  Vec<f32>                     // flat [n * STATE_DIM]
    prev_action: Vec<u32>                     // [n]
    prev_energy: Vec<f32>                     // [n]
    has_prev:    Vec<bool>                    // [n]

    // Per-slot replay buffer (ring), flat for cache friendliness:
    replay_state:      Vec<f32>               // [n * REPLAY_CAPACITY * STATE_DIM]
    replay_next_state: Vec<f32>               // [n * REPLAY_CAPACITY * STATE_DIM]
    replay_action:     Vec<u32>               // [n * REPLAY_CAPACITY]
    replay_reward:     Vec<f32>               // [n * REPLAY_CAPACITY]
    replay_done:       Vec<u8>                // [n * REPLAY_CAPACITY] — 0 or 1
    replay_write_idx:  Vec<u32>               // [n] — next slot index to overwrite
    replay_fill:       Vec<u32>               // [n] — entries valid (≤ REPLAY_CAPACITY)

    // FIX B: per-slot decision counter, drives per-slot ε decay.
    slot_decisions: Vec<u32>                  // [n] — decisions made by current
                                              //       tenant of this slot, reset
                                              //       on assign_brains_l1_hetero.

    // Global counters (telemetry / target sync only — NOT used for ε):
    decisions_made: u32                       // total ε-greedy decisions, all slots, all time
    train_steps:    u32                       // gradient updates since last target sync

    rng: SmallRng                             // for ε-greedy + replay sampling


// ============================================================================
//   6. CONSTRUCTION  (matches the existing FromWorld pattern)
// ============================================================================

impl FromWorld for BrainPoolL1Hetero:
    fn from_world(world: &mut World) -> Self:
        let n = world
            .get_resource::<OrganismPoolSize>()
            .map(|r| r.0.max(1))
            .unwrap_or(1)
        let device = CudaDevice::default()
        warmup(&device, n)                    // compile CubeCL kernels at max shape
        let online = QNetMlp::new(&device, n)
        let target = QNetMlp::new(&device, n)
        online.clone_weights_into(&mut target) // target starts == online
        return Self {
            n, online, target,
            optimizer: AdamConfig::new().init(),
            device,
            free:        (0..n as u32).rev().collect(),
            map:         HashMap::new(),
            prev_state:  vec![0.0; n * STATE_DIM],
            prev_action: vec![0;   n],
            prev_energy: vec![0.0; n],
            has_prev:    vec![false; n],
            replay_state:      vec![0.0; n * REPLAY_CAPACITY * STATE_DIM],
            replay_next_state: vec![0.0; n * REPLAY_CAPACITY * STATE_DIM],
            replay_action:     vec![0;   n * REPLAY_CAPACITY],
            replay_reward:     vec![0.0; n * REPLAY_CAPACITY],
            replay_done:       vec![0;   n * REPLAY_CAPACITY],
            replay_write_idx:  vec![0;   n],
            replay_fill:       vec![0;   n],
            slot_decisions:    vec![0;   n],   // FIX B
            decisions_made:    0,
            train_steps:       0,
            rng: SmallRng::seed_from_u64(0xAEONS),
        }


// ============================================================================
//   7. SLOT LIFECYCLE  (PreUpdate systems, chained)    [MODIFIED IN REV 2]
// ============================================================================
//
// Two changes from rev 1:
//
//   FIX A: free_brains_l1_hetero now records a TERMINAL TRANSITION before
//          releasing the slot. Without this, the (s, a, r=death, done=1)
//          tuple that ends a life is silently dropped — the network only
//          ever learns from the survivors' transitions, which carry the
//          wrong distribution over outcomes.
//
//   FIX B: assign_brains_l1_hetero resets slot_decisions[s] = 0 so the new
//          tenant's ε starts at EPSILON_START. (Weights are still inherited
//          from the previous tenant; see §12 step 9 for the alternative.)

fn assign_brains_l1_hetero(
    mut pool: NonSendMut<BrainPoolL1Hetero>,
    added:    Query<Entity, Added<Heterotroph>>,
    mut commands: Commands,
):
    for entity in added:
        if let Some(slot) = pool.free.pop():
            let s = slot as usize
            pool.map.insert(entity, slot)
            // Reset per-slot scratch. Weights stay (inherited from previous
            // tenant — gives "instinct" via prior training).
            pool.has_prev[s]        = false
            pool.replay_fill[s]     = 0
            pool.replay_write_idx[s] = 0
            pool.prev_energy[s]     = 0.0
            pool.slot_decisions[s]  = 0          // FIX B: reset ε counter.
            commands.entity(entity).try_insert(BrainSlotL1Hetero(slot))

fn free_brains_l1_hetero(
    mut pool: NonSendMut<BrainPoolL1Hetero>,
    mut removed: RemovedComponents<Heterotroph>,
):
    for entity in removed.read():
        if let Some(slot) = pool.map.remove(&entity):
            let s = slot as usize

            // FIX A: synthesise a terminal transition for the LAST decision
            // this organism took, before the slot is released. Without this
            // the network never sees the consequence of dying.
            //
            // We use prev_state as both s and s' — since done = 1, the
            // bootstrap term (1 - done) * γ * max_a' Q(s', a') is zeroed
            // and s' is unused by the TD target. We still write something
            // valid to keep tensor shapes uniform and avoid NaN propagation
            // in case a future refactor accidentally reads it.
            if pool.has_prev[s]:
                let prev_s_range = s * STATE_DIM .. (s+1) * STATE_DIM
                let prev_state: [f32; STATE_DIM] =
                    pool.prev_state[prev_s_range].try_into().unwrap()
                push_transition(
                    &mut pool, s,
                    &prev_state,
                    pool.prev_action[s],
                    DEATH_REWARD,
                    &prev_state,                   // s' = s, content irrelevant
                    1,                             // done = 1
                )
                pool.has_prev[s] = false           // belt-and-braces

            pool.free.push(slot)


// ============================================================================
//   8. BRAIN TICK  (Update, on_timer = BRAIN_TICK_INTERVAL)  [MODIFIED REV 2]
// ============================================================================
//
// Each tick, for every live heterotroph:
//   (a) encode current state                                   — §3
//   (b) if we have a prev (s, a), build (s, a, r, s', done) and
//       push to that slot's replay buffer                      — §8
//   (c) ε-greedy action selection, ε computed PER SLOT         — §8 / FIX B
//   (d) apply action: write movement_direction + movement_speed
//   (e) update prev_* cache, bump per-slot decision counter    — FIX B
//
// After the per-organism loop:
//   (f) one mini-batch gradient step                           — §9
//   (g) target-network sync if it's time                       — §9
//
// Net work per tick: N forward passes (action selection) + 1 mini-batch
// forward+backward+step. With burn-cuda batched matmul this is one GPU
// call for selection (shape [n, 1, STATE_DIM]) and one for training
// (shape [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT, STATE_DIM]).

fn apply_intelligence_level_1_hetero(
    mut pool: NonSendMut<BrainPoolL1Hetero>,
    mut q:    Query<(&mut Organism, &Transform, &BrainSlotL1Hetero)>,
    grid:     Res<WorldModelGrid>,
):
    let n = pool.n
    // ── (a, b, c, d, e): per-organism loop. ────────────────────────────
    //
    // Build a [n, 1, STATE_DIM] input tensor for action selection in ONE
    // GPU call rather than n separate forwards. We assemble it on the
    // CPU as a flat vec and upload once.
    //
    let mut act_input = vec![0.0; n * STATE_DIM]
    let mut active    = vec![false; n]          // slots with a live organism this tick

    for (organism, transform, slot_comp) in q.iter():
        let s = slot_comp.0 as usize
        if s >= n: continue
        active[s] = true

        let cur_state = encode_state(&organism, &transform, &grid)

        // (b) Build transition for the PREVIOUS decision and push to replay.
        // This is the non-terminal case; terminal transitions are pushed by
        // free_brains_l1_hetero (FIX A).
        if pool.has_prev[s]:
            let r = (organism.energy - pool.prev_energy[s]).clamp(-1.0, 1.0)
            // done is FALSE here by definition — if the organism died, it
            // wouldn't be in this query result; free_brains_l1_hetero would
            // have already handled it.
            push_transition(
                &mut pool, s,
                &pool.prev_state[s * STATE_DIM .. (s+1) * STATE_DIM],
                pool.prev_action[s],
                r,
                &cur_state,
                0,                                  // done
            )

        // Stage current state for the action-selection forward pass.
        act_input[s * STATE_DIM .. (s+1) * STATE_DIM].copy_from_slice(&cur_state)

        // Cache for the NEXT tick's transition (we still need to fill
        // prev_action below once we've chosen one).
        pool.prev_state[s * STATE_DIM .. (s+1) * STATE_DIM].copy_from_slice(&cur_state)
        pool.prev_energy[s] = organism.energy

    // ── Single batched forward for action selection. ───────────────────
    //
    // act_input: [n, STATE_DIM] → reshape to [n, 1, STATE_DIM]
    // q_values:  [n, 1, N_ACTIONS] → squeeze to [n, N_ACTIONS]
    //
    let input_t  = Tensor::from(act_input, [n, 1, STATE_DIM], pool.device)
    let q_values = pool.online.forward(input_t).squeeze(dim=1) // [n, N_ACTIONS]
    let q_cpu    = q_values.into_data().to_vec::<f32>()         // CPU mirror

    // ── (c, d, e): assign action to each live organism. ────────────────
    //
    // FIX B: ε is computed PER SLOT from slot_decisions[s], not from the
    // global counter. A newly-assigned slot starts at EPSILON_START
    // regardless of how long the pool has been running. This matters
    // because (i) the slot's replay buffer was reset on assignment so
    // exploitation of inherited weights is on shaky ground, and (ii) the
    // inherited weights may be from a completely unrelated previous
    // tenant (slot reuse is by index, not by parentage).
    for (mut organism, _, slot_comp) in q.iter_mut():
        let s = slot_comp.0 as usize
        if s >= n || !active[s]: continue

        // Per-slot linear ε schedule.
        let progress = (pool.slot_decisions[s] as f32 / EPSILON_DECAY_STEPS as f32).min(1.0)
        let epsilon  = EPSILON_START + progress * (EPSILON_END - EPSILON_START)

        let action: u32 = if pool.rng.gen::<f32>() < epsilon:
            pool.rng.gen_range(0..N_ACTIONS as u32)
        else:
            let row = &q_cpu[s * N_ACTIONS .. (s+1) * N_ACTIONS]
            argmax(row) as u32

        // (d) Apply.
        if action == 8:
            organism.movement_speed = 0.0
            // movement_direction unchanged — apply_movement must not rotate
            // the body when speed = 0 (see §2 note).
        else:
            let (dx, dz) = ACTION_DIRS[action as usize]
            organism.movement_direction = Vec3::new(dx, 0.0, dz)
            organism.movement_speed     = MAX_SPEED

        // (e) Cache action for next tick's transition.
        pool.prev_action[s]    = action
        pool.has_prev[s]       = true
        pool.slot_decisions[s] = pool.slot_decisions[s].saturating_add(1)   // FIX B
        pool.decisions_made    = pool.decisions_made.saturating_add(1)      // telemetry

    // ── (f) Training step. ──────────────────────────────────────────────
    train_dqn(&mut pool)

    // ── (g) Target sync. ────────────────────────────────────────────────
    if pool.train_steps >= TARGET_SYNC_STEPS:
        pool.online.clone_weights_into(&mut pool.target)
        pool.train_steps = 0


// ============================================================================
//   9. REPLAY + TRAINING
// ============================================================================

fn push_transition(
    pool:       &mut BrainPoolL1Hetero,
    slot:       usize,
    state:      &[f32; STATE_DIM],
    action:     u32,
    reward:     f32,
    next_state: &[f32; STATE_DIM],
    done:       u8,
):
    let i = pool.replay_write_idx[slot] as usize
    let s_base = slot * REPLAY_CAPACITY * STATE_DIM + i * STATE_DIM
    pool.replay_state    [s_base .. s_base + STATE_DIM].copy_from_slice(state)
    pool.replay_next_state[s_base .. s_base + STATE_DIM].copy_from_slice(next_state)
    let scalar_idx = slot * REPLAY_CAPACITY + i
    pool.replay_action[scalar_idx] = action
    pool.replay_reward[scalar_idx] = reward
    pool.replay_done  [scalar_idx] = done

    pool.replay_write_idx[slot] = ((i + 1) % REPLAY_CAPACITY) as u32
    if (pool.replay_fill[slot] as usize) < REPLAY_CAPACITY:
        pool.replay_fill[slot] += 1


fn train_dqn(pool: &mut BrainPoolL1Hetero):
    // ── Build mini-batch on CPU. ────────────────────────────────────────
    //
    // For each slot, sample BATCH_PER_SLOT indices uniformly from
    // [0, replay_fill[slot]). Slots without MIN_REPLAY samples contribute
    // zeros and are masked out of the loss.
    //
    // Final shapes (all flat):
    //   s_batch   : [n * BATCH_PER_SLOT * STATE_DIM]
    //   ns_batch  : [n * BATCH_PER_SLOT * STATE_DIM]
    //   a_batch   : [n * BATCH_PER_SLOT]
    //   r_batch   : [n * BATCH_PER_SLOT]
    //   d_batch   : [n * BATCH_PER_SLOT]
    //   mask_batch: [n * BATCH_PER_SLOT]   (1.0 if slot trained this tick, else 0.0)

    let n = pool.n
    let s_batch:  Vec<f32> = zeros(n * BATCH_PER_SLOT * STATE_DIM)
    let ns_batch: Vec<f32> = zeros(n * BATCH_PER_SLOT * STATE_DIM)
    let a_batch:  Vec<u32> = zeros(n * BATCH_PER_SLOT)
    let r_batch:  Vec<f32> = zeros(n * BATCH_PER_SLOT)
    let d_batch:  Vec<f32> = zeros(n * BATCH_PER_SLOT)
    let mask:     Vec<f32> = zeros(n * BATCH_PER_SLOT)

    let mut any_active = false
    for s in 0..n:
        if pool.replay_fill[s] < MIN_REPLAY as u32: continue
        any_active = true
        let fill = pool.replay_fill[s] as usize
        for b in 0..BATCH_PER_SLOT:
            let i = pool.rng.gen_range(0..fill)
            // Copy state[s][i] into s_batch[s][b], etc.
            let src_s = s * REPLAY_CAPACITY * STATE_DIM + i * STATE_DIM
            let dst_s = s * BATCH_PER_SLOT  * STATE_DIM + b * STATE_DIM
            s_batch [dst_s .. dst_s + STATE_DIM].copy_from(&pool.replay_state    [src_s .. src_s + STATE_DIM])
            ns_batch[dst_s .. dst_s + STATE_DIM].copy_from(&pool.replay_next_state[src_s .. src_s + STATE_DIM])
            let src_scalar = s * REPLAY_CAPACITY + i
            let dst_scalar = s * BATCH_PER_SLOT  + b
            a_batch[dst_scalar] = pool.replay_action[src_scalar]
            r_batch[dst_scalar] = pool.replay_reward[src_scalar]
            d_batch[dst_scalar] = pool.replay_done  [src_scalar] as f32
            mask  [dst_scalar] = 1.0

    if !any_active: return                  // not enough data anywhere yet

    // ── Upload to GPU as [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT, ...]. ─────────────────────
    let s_t  = Tensor::from(s_batch,  [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT, STATE_DIM], pool.device)
    let ns_t = Tensor::from(ns_batch, [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT, STATE_DIM], pool.device)
    let a_t  = Tensor::from(a_batch,  [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT],            pool.device)  // int64 indices
    let r_t  = Tensor::from(r_batch,  [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT],            pool.device)
    let d_t  = Tensor::from(d_batch,  [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT],            pool.device)
    let m_t  = Tensor::from(mask,     [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT],            pool.device)

    // ── Q(s, a) from the ONLINE network (carries gradient). ────────────
    //
    // q_pred:    [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT, N_ACTIONS]
    // q_pred_a:  [n, BATCH_PER_SLOT]               — gathered at the action index
    //
    let q_pred   = pool.online.forward(s_t)
    let q_pred_a = gather(q_pred, dim = -1, index = a_t.unsqueeze(-1)).squeeze(-1)

    // ── max_a' Q_target(s', a') from the TARGET network. NO GRADIENT. ──
    //
    // Computed inside a no-grad scope; the result is detached before use.
    //
    let q_next_max = no_grad:
        let q_next = pool.target.forward(ns_t)                     // [n, B, N_ACTIONS]
        q_next.max(dim = -1).detach()                              // [n, B]

    // ── TD target. (1 − done) zeros the bootstrap on terminal transitions.
    //     FIX A relies on this: terminal transitions pushed by
    //     free_brains_l1_hetero have done = 1, so their target is exactly
    //     DEATH_REWARD with no bootstrap from the (meaningless) next state.
    let td_target = r_t + GAMMA * q_next_max * (1.0 - d_t)
    let td_target = td_target.detach()                              // belt and braces

    // ── Huber loss per sample (robust to predation reward spikes). ─────
    //
    //   L(e) = ½·e²            if |e| < δ
    //        = δ·(|e| − ½·δ)   otherwise
    //
    let td_err   = q_pred_a - td_target                             // [n, B]
    let abs_err  = td_err.abs()
    let quad     = 0.5 * td_err.powi(2)
    let linear   = HUBER_DELTA * (abs_err - 0.5 * HUBER_DELTA)
    let per_sample = where(abs_err < HUBER_DELTA, quad, linear)     // [n, B]

    // ── Mask + reduce. Each row independent; loss is the mean over
    //    active (slot, batch-idx) pairs. Dividing by m_t.sum() (not by
    //    n × BATCH_PER_SLOT) keeps the effective gradient magnitude
    //    independent of how many slots are currently trainable. ──────
    let masked = per_sample * m_t
    let denom  = m_t.sum().clamp(1.0, infinity)                     // avoid div-by-0
    let loss   = masked.sum() / denom

    // ── Gradient step (with norm clipping). ────────────────────────────
    let grads = loss.backward()
    let grads = grads.clip_norm(GRAD_CLIP_NORM)                     // standard DQN trick
    pool.online = pool.optimizer.step(LR, pool.online, grads)
    pool.train_steps = pool.train_steps.saturating_add(1)


// ============================================================================
//  10. WARMUP  (CubeCL kernel pre-compile, identical pattern to current pool)
// ============================================================================

fn warmup(device: &CudaDevice, n: usize):
    // Construct dummy online + target nets and one mini-batch at the
    // maximum shape, run one forward + Huber loss + backward + step.
    // CubeCL caches every kernel the hot path will invoke.
    let online = QNetMlp::new(device, n)
    let mut optimizer = AdamConfig::new().init()
    let s_t  = Tensor::zeros([n, BATCH_PER_SLOT, STATE_DIM], device)
    let ns_t = Tensor::zeros([n, BATCH_PER_SLOT, STATE_DIM], device)
    let a_t  = Tensor::zeros([n, BATCH_PER_SLOT], device)
    let r_t  = Tensor::zeros([n, BATCH_PER_SLOT], device)
    let d_t  = Tensor::zeros([n, BATCH_PER_SLOT], device)
    let m_t  = Tensor::ones ([n, BATCH_PER_SLOT], device)
    // ... same loss block as train_dqn ...
    let _ = optimizer.step(LR, online, loss.backward())


// ============================================================================
//  11. SAVE / LOAD
// ============================================================================
//
// The on-disk snapshot needs three weight matrices per slot:
//     w1 [STATE_DIM × HIDDEN], b1 [HIDDEN],
//     w2 [HIDDEN × HIDDEN],    b2 [HIDDEN],
//     w3 [HIDDEN × N_ACTIONS], b3 [N_ACTIONS]
//
// Drop the old PoolSnapshot's policy / value-head fields; replace with the
// three Q-net layers. The replay buffer is NOT serialised — a restored
// organism starts with empty replay and re-fills from new experience.
// The target network is also not serialised — initialised to == online on
// load. The per-slot slot_decisions counter is NOT serialised either: on
// load, treat every restored slot as a fresh tenant (slot_decisions = 0)
// so its ε starts at EPSILON_START. This is consistent with the empty
// replay buffer — the loaded weights are a prior, not ground truth.


// ============================================================================
//  12. INTEGRATION CHECKLIST
// ============================================================================
//
// To turn this design into compilable Rust:
//
//   1. Translate this file into `intelligence_level_1_hetero.rs`, deleting
//      the existing REINFORCE/A2C body. Keep the file path and the
//      `BrainPoolL1Hetero`, `BrainSlotL1Hetero` type names so other modules
//      (`colony.rs` save/load, `behaviour.rs` schedule, `rl_helpers.rs`)
//      don't need renaming.
//
//   2. `behaviour.rs::BehaviourPlugin::build` already calls
//      `init_non_send_resource::<BrainPoolL1Hetero>()` and registers the
//      `assign_brains_l1_hetero` / `free_brains_l1_hetero` /
//      `apply_intelligence_level_1_hetero` systems with the right schedule
//      placement. CONFIRM that free_brains_l1_hetero runs in PostUpdate or
//      similar — i.e. AFTER the death-causing system (energy depletion,
//      predation) and AFTER any system that despawns dead heterotrophs
//      removes the Heterotroph component. The FIX A terminal-transition
//      push needs to happen on the SAME frame the organism dies, while
//      pool.prev_state[s] is still valid.
//
//   3. `apply_movement` already consumes `movement_direction` and
//      `movement_speed`. VERIFY it does not rotate the body when
//      movement_speed == 0 (the STOP action depends on this — see §2).
//
//   4. Delete reward shaping in this file. The single reward channel is
//      `r = clamp(Δenergy, ±1)` for non-terminal steps and DEATH_REWARD
//      for terminal steps. Predation events produce positive spikes;
//      everything else is ~0. Q-learning + replay handles the sparsity.
//
//   5. Delete `BrainOptL1Hetero` and the value head. DQN has no policy
//      head and no value head — just Q.
//
//   6. Update `PoolSnapshot` / `BrainRestore` in `rl_helpers.rs` to the
//      new field set (§11 above).
//
//   7. Update CLAUDE.md to replace the REINFORCE-with-baseline narrative
//      under "Behaviour: two intelligence levels" with a DQN description.
//      Mention: per-slot ε, angular-bin prey encoding, terminal-on-death.
//
//   8. Photoautotroph pool (`intelligence_level_1_photo.rs`) is OUT OF
//      SCOPE for this rewrite. It can keep its current oracle-MSE
//      approach (the audit didn't cover it because the user's question
//      was about prey pursuit specifically).
//
//   9. OPTIONAL — "fresh weights per birth". The current design has slots
//      inherit weights from their previous tenants ("instinct via prior
//      training"). This is a population-level prior, NOT genealogical
//      inheritance — slot reuse is by free-list LIFO, not by parentage.
//      If the simulation produces unwanted lock-in (whole population
//      converging on a single early policy), try calling
//      `pool.online.reinit_slot(s, &pool.device)` and the matching
//      target reinit inside assign_brains_l1_hetero. This decouples
//      newborns from their slot's history at the cost of slower group
//      convergence. Keep one or the other behind a const flag for
//      experimentation.
//
//
// Expected behaviour after rewrite, with the new cohort settings
// (500 photo + 80 hetero, AI_TRAINING_MODE = false):
//
//   • First ~30s per heterotroph: ε ≈ 1.0, pure random walks. Per-slot
//     decision counter is small. Replay buffer fills toward MIN_REPLAY.
//   • 30s–7 min per heterotroph: ε decays linearly toward 0.05 over its
//     own 4k decisions. Bellman updates start refining Q-values around
//     predation events AND death events (FIX A). Heterotrophs that die
//     young contribute terminal transitions that other slots can't see
//     directly but that shape the per-slot weights of whoever inherits
//     this slot next.
//   • 30+ min wall clock: visible pursuit behaviour emerges in the
//     longer-lived heterotrophs. New heterotrophs inherit weights from
//     their slot's previous tenant and bootstrap noticeably faster than
//     the first generation did.
//
//   • If pursuit does NOT emerge after ~2 hours, suspect (in order):
//       a) Death penalty too small relative to predation reward — log
//          a histogram of replay_reward; if predation reward spikes are
//          regularly larger than 1.0 before clamping, the clamp is
//          starving the positive signal. Consider widening the clamp
//          to ±5 and matching DEATH_REWARD = -5.
//       b) Prey too sparse in the world → reduce WORLD_MODEL_RADIUS or
//          increase INITIAL_PHOTOAUTOTROPHS.
//       c) γ too high — try γ = 0.9 for shorter credit-assignment horizon.
//       d) ε floor too high — reduce EPSILON_END to 0.01.
//       e) BATCH_PER_SLOT too small — try 64.
//       f) Try the "fresh weights per birth" path (step 9). If pursuit
//          emerges with fresh weights but not with inherited weights,
//          the population is stuck in a bad local optimum that
//          inheritance is preserving.
//
//
// ============================================================================
//   DESIGN NOTES — REV 2 (full rationale for the three fixes)
// ============================================================================
//
// ── FIX A: terminal transitions on death ────────────────────────────────────
//
// The bug: in rev 1, transitions were built in apply_intelligence_level_1_hetero
// from prev_state/prev_action against the CURRENT tick's state. An organism
// that died between tick t and tick t+1 was no longer in the Query at tick
// t+1, so the (s, a, r, s', done=1) tuple for its last decision was never
// pushed. The network's replay buffer contained only transitions where the
// organism survived. The implicit message to the optimiser was "every action
// I've ever taken led to me being alive afterwards" — which is true of the
// data but useless for learning to avoid death.
//
// The fix: free_brains_l1_hetero now synthesises the terminal transition
// before pushing the slot back on the free list. Reward is the fixed
// DEATH_REWARD constant (-1.0), done = 1, so the TD target collapses to
// r alone — no bootstrap from a fictitious next state. The next-state
// content is filled with prev_state to keep tensor shapes uniform; the
// (1 - done) multiplier ensures it never influences the target.
//
// Why a fixed death penalty rather than r = -prev_energy: the latter is
// scale-coupled to max_energy and to the Δenergy clamp. A fixed -1.0,
// matching the running reward clamp, keeps the magnitudes commensurate.
// If you find the clamp is starving the positive signal (see §12 failure
// mode (a)), widen both DEATH_REWARD and the clamp together.
//
// Subtle point on scheduling: free_brains_l1_hetero must run AFTER the
// system that removes the Heterotroph component on death, but on the SAME
// frame, while pool.prev_state[s] still holds the state at the organism's
// last decision. If the death-handling system runs on frame N and slot
// release runs on frame N+1, the prev_state may have been written by a
// (stale) earlier read in apply_intelligence_level_1_hetero on frame N+1.
// Worth a unit test: spawn a heterotroph, set its energy to a known value,
// let it tick once (recording prev_state), then despawn it and assert that
// replay_state at its slot contains the expected state.
//
// ── FIX B: per-slot ε schedule ───────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// The bug: rev 1's single global decisions_made counter meant ε decayed
// according to wall-clock simulation activity, not according to any single
// organism's lifetime. With ~80 heterotrophs deciding at ~10 Hz, the global
// counter hit EPSILON_DECAY_STEPS = 100k in ~125 seconds. Any heterotroph
// born after that point started with ε = 0.05 — almost no exploration —
// despite having an empty replay buffer and (often) inherited weights from
// an unrelated previous tenant.
//
// Worse, the slot-inheritance design means a newborn's weights are NOT its
// parent's weights. Slot reuse follows the free-list LIFO, so a newborn
// gets whoever-died-most-recently's brain. With near-zero ε, that newborn
// would immediately exploit the inherited policy, never building its own
// replay buffer's understanding of how those weights actually correspond
// to its situation. Compounded across generations, the population gets
// stuck on whatever the first-minute survivors converged on.
//
// The fix: slot_decisions[s] is a per-slot counter, reset to 0 on
// assign_brains_l1_hetero. ε is computed locally from it. EPSILON_DECAY_STEPS
// drops from 100k to 4k because it now represents a single organism's
// experience budget, not the whole population's. At 10 Hz that's ~7 minutes
// of life per heterotroph spent transitioning from explore to exploit.
//
// The global decisions_made counter is kept for telemetry — useful for
// dashboards but never read by the policy.
//
// Note: this fix does NOT change the inheritance behaviour. A newborn still
// inherits its slot's previous tenant's weights. The per-slot ε reset just
// guarantees it gets enough exploration to discover whether those weights
// are useful for its actual situation. See §12 step 9 for the alternative
// of resetting weights too.
//
// ── FIX C: permutation-invariant prey encoding ──────────────────────────────
//
// The bug: rev 1 encoded the four nearest prey, sorted by distance, into
// fixed slots [2..6], [6..10], [10..14], [14..18]. Two issues:
//   1. When prey A and prey B were near-equidistant, their positions in
//      the state vector flipped tick-to-tick. The network sees
//         [..., A_pos, B_pos, ...] and [..., B_pos, A_pos, ...]
//      as different inputs and must learn the permutation invariance from
//      data. With sparse predation rewards, it never gets enough data.
//   2. The "empty slot = all zeros" convention meant that "no prey here"
//      and "prey at the origin" produced identical state in three of the
//      four fields. The is_visible flag was the only differentiator.
//
// The fix: 8 angular sectors around the body frame, each reporting the
// nearest prey's distance and an occupied flag. Total: 8 × 2 = 16 fields,
// matching the rev 1 layout's STATE_DIM = 18.
//
// Properties of the new encoding:
//   • Permuting prey within a sector: no change.
//   • Permuting prey across sectors: state changes as the world changed.
//   • A prey moving from one sector to the next: continuous in distance
//     within each sector; discontinuous only at the sector boundary, and
//     even there the magnitude of the discontinuity is bounded (a prey at
//     the boundary at distance d shows up in one bin at d, then in the
//     next bin at d — same distance, different angular index).
//   • An empty bin's distance is 1.0 (max), not 0.0 (origin), so a future
//     prey appearing at the radius edge produces a smooth transition in
//     the distance channel: 1.0 → 1.0, occupied 0.0 → 1.0. Only one
//     channel changes abruptly.
//   • A scene with 1 prey looks like 7 empty bins + 1 occupied bin, not
//     like "3 fictitious prey at the origin", which was rev 1's behaviour.
//
// Cost: information loss when many prey crowd a single sector — only the
// nearest is reported. For a 60-unit radius with 8 sectors (45° each), a
// sector at the radius edge covers an arc of ~47 units. Multiple prey per
// sector are likely in crowded scenes. If pursuit is observed but the
// organism behaves badly in dense schools, consider increasing N_PREY_BINS
// to 12 or 16 (and STATE_DIM accordingly), or adding a "count in bin" field
// (would push PREY_FIELDS to 3 and STATE_DIM to 26).
//
// Subtle point on the angular convention: the +z axis is body-frame
// "forward", and the inverse-yaw rotation in encode_state() puts a world
// prey directly in front of the organism at body coordinates (0, +d).
// atan2(body_x, body_z) gives 0 for "directly ahead", positive for "to
// the right" (clockwise when viewed from above with +y up), negative for
// "to the left". After the [0, 2π) shift, bin 0 covers [0°, 45°), i.e.
// straight ahead to ahead-right. Sanity-check this against the Bevy
// coordinate convention before shipping — Bevy's default is right-handed
// y-up, but YXZ Euler decomposition is the convention being used here.
//
// ============================================================================
//                              END OF DESIGN
// ============================================================================
